This week’s work focused on building a 3D scene in Godot and thinking about how space can function as part of storytelling. 
In the reading, Henry Jenkins discusses the idea of “narrative architecture,” arguing that game environments are not just backgrounds 
but spaces that structure how stories are experienced. Players move through these environments as both participants and observers, 
discovering story elements through exploration. Designing a 3D scene in Godot helped me better understand this idea because it required 
me to think about how the placement of objects, paths, and spaces could guide a player’s experience.

For my scene, I created a small 3D landscape that functions like a still life environment. I used basic shapes such as pillars, rocks, trees, 
and crates to construct the space. Even though these objects are simple, arranging them made me think about how environments can suggest meaning 
or invite exploration. For example, placing objects in certain positions can make the player curious about what might be behind them or encourage 
them to move toward a particular area of the scene.

Adding a controllable character also changed how I thought about the environment. When the player can move through the space, the scene becomes 
less like a static image and more like a world that unfolds over time. Movement allows the player to explore from different angles and notice details 
they might not see otherwise. This made me realize that narrative in games often comes from the act of exploring rather than from explicit dialogue or text.

This idea connects closely to the game Gone Home. In Gone Home, the player explores a house and pieces together the story by interacting with objects and 
reading notes left behind. The narrative is embedded in the environment rather than presented directly. As Jenkins suggests, the architecture of the space 
itself guides the story experience. Rooms, locked doors, and hidden areas encourage players to explore and slowly uncover the narrative.

Working with Godot helped me better understand how environment design influences storytelling. Even a simple 3D scene can shape how a player moves, 
what they notice, and what they discover. Designing the space made me think about how objects and layout can imply a story without explicitly telling it. 
This experience reinforced Jenkins’s argument that game spaces are full of narrative potential and that storytelling in games often emerges from the player’s 
interaction with the environment.
